<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 10:11<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If67e08716b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I6059a720933c11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>10.</label.designator><headtext>Remand</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94fa052ae1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>10:11.</label.designator><headtext>Specific factors relating to remand—Dissatisfaction with transferee court rulings</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Not surprisingly in view of the Panel&apos;s overall lack of sympathy with arguments relating to a party&apos;s dissatisfaction with the rulings of the transferee court,[<footnote.reference refid="If67e2f806b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>] this factor will not support a motion for remand.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If67e2f836b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>] Indeed, as in other motions before the Panel, the direct advancing of this factor by a party or the Panel&apos;s sensing that it in fact motivates a motion for remand will probably make remand less likely.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If67e56906b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Panel has rejected arguments that remand should be ordered because of the prior actions or rulings of the transferee judge.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If67e56926b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">4</footnote.reference>] This type of argument is regularly rejected be cause it does not address proper considerations of the Panel and because it would permit a party an improper opportunity to “judge-shop.”[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If67e56936b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">5</footnote.reference>] In one case the transferee judge bifurcated the issues, ordering discovery and trial on one group of issues to be followed by trial and discovery and trial on the remaining issues. <eos/><bos/>The Panel declined to order remand because of the transferee court&apos;s wide latitude in conducting coordinated or consolidated pretrial proceedings in the transferred actions.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If67e56956b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">6</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If67e08716b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If67e2f806b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>This factor is discussed in §§ <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs5:36" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If67e2f816b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">5:36</cite.query> and  <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs5:41" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If67e2f826b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">5:41</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If67e2f836b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See, e.g.</ital>, <cite.query w-src-number="0304914141" w-serial-number="1977125580" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="1126" ID="I71c411116b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">In re Holiday Magic Securities and Antitrust Litigation, 433 F. Supp. 1125, 1126 (J.P.M.L. 1977)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If67e56906b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs5:41" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If67e56916b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 5:41</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If67e56926b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See, e.g.</ital>, <cite.query w-src-number="0304914141" w-serial-number="1981114874" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="1226" ID="I71c522816b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">In re Data General Corp. Antitrust Litigation, 510 F. Supp. 1220, 1226 (J.P.M.L. 1979)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0304914141" w-serial-number="1977125580" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="1126" ID="I71c522836b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">In re Holiday Magic Securities and Antitrust Litigation, 433 F. Supp. 1125, 1126 (J.P.M.L. 1977)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0304914141" w-serial-number="1971106847" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="1048" ID="I71c522856b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">In re Plumbing Fixtures, 332 F. Supp. 1047, 1048 (J.P.M.L. 1971)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If67e56936b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Panel&apos;s refusal to consider the prior rulings of the transferee judge as part of its initial decision on transfer is discussed in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs5:41" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If67e56946b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 5:41</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/><ital>See generally</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304914141" w-serial-number="1975107932" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="1406" ID="I71c5bec16b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">In re Molinaro/Catanzaro Patent Litigation, 402 F. Supp. 1404, 1406 (J.P.M.L. 1975)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0304914141" w-serial-number="1973107468" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="806" ID="I71c5bec36b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">In re Glenn W. Turner Enterprises Litigation, 368 F. Supp. 805, 806 (J.P.M.L. 1973)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If67e56956b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See, e.g.</ital>, <cite.query w-src-number="0304914141" w-serial-number="1981114874" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="1226" ID="I71c65b016b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">In re Data General Corp. Antitrust Litigation, 510 F. Supp. 1220, 1226 (J.P.M.L. 1979)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. 